      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1007_s00216_023_05070_2__task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The candidate card frames the task narrowly as 'how does pyOpenMS ingest and produce', suggesting a mechanistic/implementation question. The paper describes pyOpenMS as a tool used within PF\u0394Screen's workflow but does not provide detailed algorithmic or implementation documentation of pyOpenMS itself. The paper documents the INPUT (centroided mzML) and OUTPUT (feature list) but not the internal mechanics of pyOpenMS feature detection.",
        "The paper mentions that 'For feature detection, the FeatureFinderMetabo algorithm is used, which is designed for metabolites and small molecules' but does not explain how this algorithm works internally\u2014only that it is used and what parameters can be specified (mass error, intensity threshold, isotope model).",
        "The task card's framing as 'reconstruct the mzML feature detection step' is consistent with the paper's scope (PF\u0394Screen does perform this step), but the paper does not provide sufficient detail to fully reconstruct the internal workings of pyOpenMS\u2014only its role in the workflow."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:24:37.501006+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1007_s00216_023_05070_2__task_002/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Recently, a promising approach based on the MD normalized to the carbon number (MD/C) vs. the mass normalized to the carbon number (m/C) was proposed to separate PFAS much more efficiently from other hydrocarbon features in HRMS data... The carbon number can be easily estimated for all HRMS features by using the relative abundance of the M+1 isotope (13C). PFAS have a much higher m/C when their mass is dominated by fluorine (e.g., m/C ~ 50), while hydrocarbons of similar mass are dominated by carbon (m/C ~ 14), allowing a convenient separation.",
      "asbval:note": "Research question directly addresses the MD/C-m/C approach for PFAS feature filtering and prioritization, which is a core technique described in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1007-s00216-023-05070-2",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How does the MD/C-m/C approach filter and prioritize potential PFAS features from a mass spectrometry feature list?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:24:52.817281+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
