    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mzml-file-parsing/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "PF\u0394Screen is a fully automated tool for detection and prioritization of potential PFAS features (LC- or GC-HRMS with ESI or APCI source) in raw mass spectrometric data... Input MS raw data can be converted vendor-independently from data-dependent acquisition (ddMS2) files into the mzML data format (.mzML)... After feature detection, the MS raw data can be directly visualized via the PF\u0394Screen GUI",
      "asbval:note": "Scope aligns with paper's description of LC/GC-HRMS with ESI/APCI and vendor-independent mzML processing.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1007-s00216-023-05070-2",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mzml-file-parsing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope \u2014 when to use",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have raw LC- or GC-HRMS data from vendor instruments (ESI or APCI ionization) that needs to be converted to a vendor-neutral format for non-target screening, or you already have mzML files that require loading into a Python environment for downstream feature detection and MS2",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:21.228236+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mzml-file-parsing/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Only mzML files with centroided spectra and one collision energy (CE) should be used. If profile data was acquired and MS2 spectra from several different CEs per precursor m/z are present, the peak picking (for centroiding) and subset functions (from MSConvert) can be used to generate the correct mzML input files.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states that centroided spectra are required and provides guidance on handling profile data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1007-s00216-023-05070-2",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mzml-file-parsing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope \u2014 when NOT to use (profile data)",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Raw data is in profile (centroid-like but not centroided) format without explicit centroid annotation \u2014 pyOpenMS feature detection expects true centroided spectra; profile data may produce spurious or low-confidence features.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:21.228236+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mzml-file-parsing/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In the MS2 data, lists of PFAS-specific diagnostic fragments (DFs) as well as fragment mass differences and neutral losses can be used to prioritize fragmentation spectra... For all MS2 spectra, fragment mass differences are calculated comprehensively... Furthermore, a list of typical PFAS diagnostic fragments (DFs, approximately 900 fragments) from literature are automatically matched with all fragmentation spectra",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms MS2 data is essential for diagnostic fragment and mass difference matching in PFAS prioritization.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1007-s00216-023-05070-2",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mzml-file-parsing",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope \u2014 when NOT to use (MS2 requirement)",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "mzML file lacks MS2 data (MS1-only or survey scan data) and diagnostic fragment matching is required for PFAS prioritization \u2014 MS2 spectra are essential for the fragment mass difference and diagnostic fragment filtering steps.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:21.228236+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pfas-characteristic-mass-difference-detection/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For all MS2 spectra, fragment mass differences are calculated comprehensively. Therefore, all fragment differences within each MS2 spectrum are calculated and matched against a predefined list of PFAS typical mass differences (e.g., \u0394CF2, \u0394C2F4, \u0394HF, \u0394C10H3F17, more details can be found in [31]). This allows an efficient detection of fragments indicative for PFAS without prior knowledge on their actual mass [23, 31]. Furthermore, a list of typical PFAS diagnostic fragments (DFs, approximately 900 fragments) from literature are automatically matched with all fragmentation spectra... PFAS feature prioritization (2) includes techniques such as the MD/C-m/C approach, KMD analysis, fragment matching, and fragment mass differences which generates a strongly reduced feature list of potential PFAS.",
      "asbval:note": "Claim is directly supported. The paper explicitly describes detection of diagnostic fragment mass differences (\u0394CF2, \u0394C2F4, \u0394HF) in MS2 spectra and their use alongside MD/C-m/C and KMD analysis for PFAS prioritization.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1007-s00216-023-05070-2",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pfas-characteristic-mass-difference-detection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Identifies potential PFAS features in LC/GC-HRMS data by detecting diagnostic fragment mass differences in MS2 spectra that are characteristic of PFAS structures (e.g., CF\u2082 repeating units). This technique prioritizes candidate features alongside Kendrick mass defect and MD/C-m/C",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:37.497282+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pfas-characteristic-mass-difference-detection/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Feature detection from vendor-independent MS raw data (mzML, data-dependent acquisition) is performed via pyOpenMS (or custom feature lists) with subsequent calculations for prioritization and identification of PFAS in both HPLC- and GC-HRMS data... This task is performed with pyOpenMS, a Python interface to the C++ OpenMS library [42\u201346]. For feature detection, the FeatureFinderMetabo algorithm is used, which is designed for metabolites and small molecules [47\u201349].",
      "asbval:note": "pyOpenMS is confirmed as the tool used for MS data parsing and feature detection from mzML files.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1007-s00216-023-05070-2",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pfas-characteristic-mass-difference-detection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "pyOpenMS \u2014 Parse centroided MS2 spectra from mzML and extract precursor\u2013product mass pairs for diagnostic fragment matching",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:32:37.497282+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pfas-characteristic-mass-difference-detection/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "This task is performed with pyOpenMS, a Python interface to the C++ OpenMS library [42\u201346].",
      "asbval:note": "OpenMS is confirmed as the underlying C++ library accessed via pyOpenMS.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1007-s00216-023-05070-2",
